{# ---- The reframe ------------------------------------------------------- #}
<section class="ff-section">
  <div class="ff-wrap ff-split">
    <div class="ff-split-text ff-rv">
      <p class="ff-eyebrow">What is really happening</p>
      <h2 class="ff-h2">Your alarm is working. <em>It is just set too sensitive.</em></h2>
      <p class="ff-desc">If you're here, some part of your day has probably started to organize itself around worry. The 3 a.m. replay of a conversation. The meeting you rehearse twenty times. The plans you quietly turn down. Anxiety is a smoke detector that has grown a little too sensitive, going off for burnt toast as loudly as for a real fire.</p>
      <p class="ff-desc">The alarm is real. The danger usually isn't. So how do we help it tell the difference again? That's usually where we start, and you don't have to sort it out alone.</p>
      <p class="ff-pullquote">That's not a character flaw. That's just how the nervous system works.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ff-photo-needed ff-rv ff-d1">
      <span class="ff-ph-icon">{{ icoCamera | safe }}</span>
      <p class="ff-ph-lbl">Photo to source</p>
      <p class="ff-ph-desc">One person on the sand at a distance, shoulders down, looking at the water. Room to breathe in the frame.</p>
      <p class="ff-ph-path">coastal set, pending on the CDN</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{# ---- What anxiety is doing --------------------------------------------- #}
<section class="ff-section ff-band-sand">
  <div class="ff-wrap">
    <div class="ff-head ff-head--center ff-rv">
      <p class="ff-eyebrow">The pattern</p>
      <h2 class="ff-h2">What anxiety is actually doing.</h2>
      <p class="ff-desc">Three moving parts, and none of them mean something is wrong with you.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ff-cards">
      <article class="ff-card ff-rv">
        <span class="ff-card-icon">{{ icoWave | safe }}</span>
        <h3>The worry loop</h3>
        <p>Worry promises that if you think it through one more time, you'll finally feel safe. So you do, and the relief lasts about a minute before the next what-if arrives. The loop feels productive. Mostly it's exhausting.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="ff-card ff-rv ff-d1">
        <span class="ff-card-icon">{{ icoHeart | safe }}</span>
        <h3>The body's alarm</h3>
        <p>Racing heart, tight chest, the sense that something is about to go wrong. Your body is running a threat response built for lions, not inboxes. Nothing is broken. The wiring is doing exactly what it evolved to do.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="ff-card ff-rv ff-d2">
        <span class="ff-card-icon">{{ icoCompass | safe }}</span>
        <h3>The avoidance trap</h3>
        <p>Skipping the thing that scares you works, for an afternoon. Then the world quietly shrinks, and the list of off-limits places and conversations grows. Avoidance is a loan with a very high interest rate.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{# ---- The many shapes it takes (the SEO section) ------------------------ #}
<section class="ff-section" id="the-work">
  <div class="ff-wrap">
    <div class="ff-head ff-rv">
      <p class="ff-eyebrow">The many shapes it takes</p>
      <h2 class="ff-h2">Panic attacks, phobias, and <em>social anxiety.</em></h2>
      <p class="ff-desc">Anxiety rarely shows up in the abstract. It picks a shape. Here are the three we see most, and what the work looks like for each.</p>
    </div>
    <ul class="ff-forms">
      <li class="ff-form ff-rv">
        <span class="ff-form-icon">{{ icoHeart | safe }}</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Panic attacks</h3>
          <p>A panic attack can feel like a heart attack: the pounding chest, the dizziness, the certainty that something is very wrong. Panic disorder is the fear of the next one, which quietly keeps the cycle going. Panic is treatable, and understanding what's happening is often the first turn.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="ff-form ff-rv ff-d1">
        <span class="ff-form-icon">{{ icoShield | safe }}</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Phobias</h3>
          <p>Flying, driving the 405, needles, heights, deep water. A phobia is fear that has narrowed onto one specific thing and dug in. Phobia treatment works by helping you approach it in steps small enough to stay with, until the fear loosens its grip.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="ff-form ff-rv ff-d2">
        <span class="ff-form-icon">{{ icoChat | safe }}</span>
        <div>
          <h3>Social anxiety</h3>
          <p>If being watched, judged, or noticed at all sends your stomach into free fall, that's social anxiety, sometimes called social phobia. We work on the beliefs underneath it, and practice, gently, until connection feels less like a performance.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

